    fullDescription: "Utrecht, the Netherlands' fourth-largest city, is an appealing and characterful full-day trip just twenty-five to thirty minutes south of Amsterdam by frequent trains. Its signature feature is unique in the country: the medieval canals run on two levels, with the water flanked by lower wharves (werven) that were once used for unloading goods and are now lined with atmospheric waterside cafés, terraces and restaurants right at the water's edge — a lovely setting for lunch or a drink. Towering over the centre is the Dom Tower, the tallest church tower in the Netherlands, which you can climb (guided) for panoramic views; the cathedral it once adjoined was partly destroyed centuries ago, leaving the tower dramatically separated from the choir. A youthful, lively place thanks to its large university, Utrecht also offers good museums (including the quirky Museum Speelklok of self-playing musical instruments and the Miffy/Dick Bruna connection), independent shops and a relaxed, less touristy feel than Amsterdam. It's compact and very walkable, easy to explore in a day of canal-side strolling, tower-climbing, museum-hopping and café-lingering. For a rewarding Dutch city break with a distinctive twist, Utrecht makes an excellent and easy day trip.",
